String txt_NationalsozialismusErlangen_en = "After a large-scale \"purge\" of the public service, which did not affect any jewish citizens in Erlangen, the next major action by the National Socialists against the Jews in 1933 was the mass placarding of Jewish shops. On April 1 at around 10 a.m., the SA placed signs in front of many shops on which was written: \"Germans! Defend yourselves! Don't buy from Jews! \". This turned out to be a severe blow to the jewish community as the majority of Jews were in the trading business. One month later, on May 12, SA officers publicly burned over 1,500 books as well as 1,000 newspapers and magazines containing socially critical, jewish or other forbidden ideas.\nIn July, the police searched all of the shops and premises of jewish organizations in Erlangen. In the process, property and assets were often confiscated.\nOn August 2nd Mayor Groß gave the order that all Jews were prohibited from entering the Röthelheimbad. There even were two posters at the entrance of the bath with the inscription \"Jews are prohibited from entering\".\nIn October the memorial of the jewish university professor Herz first got degraded and then destroyed.\nThis all led to the first wave of emigration in 1933, after that instead of 117 there were only 65 Jews who lived in Erlangen in 1934.\nThe Nuremberg Laws:\nThe National Socialists also tried to drive Jews out of the cattle trade. However, since this part of the economy was dominated by jewish cattle dealers - there were 292 Jewish and 149 non-Jewish cattle dealers in Erlangen - this process lasted until the end of 1938.\nThe Jewish community in Erlangen tried to help the growing number of Jewswho needed support. However, since they lacked money and resources, they sought support from larger communities such as Nuremberg, Fürth or Würzburg.\nThe Nuremberg Laws, which were promulgated on September 15, 1935, consisted of three individual laws. The \"Reich Citizenship Law\" and the \"Blood Protection Law\" had a particularly great influence on the jewish part of the population.\nThe Reich Citizenship Law divided the Germans into Reich Citizens and Citizens. Since only members of \"German or related blood\" were citizens of the Reich, therefore only these had full access to civil rights. Jews were therefore not allowed to hold public office and lost their voting rights. The Blood Protection Act, or in the original \"Law for the Protection of German Blood and German Honor\", forbade Jews and Aryans to marry and to commit extramarital sexual intercourse. Jews were also forbidden from employing a maid with \"German blood\" who was younger than 45 years of age in their household. In Erlangen, this meant that Jews from Erlangen were no longer allowed to employ long-term employees in the household and employment relationships had to be terminated. Requests for continued employment were also made, as in the case of Mr Weinstock, who asked to be allowed to keep his domestic help because, as a 76-year-old he posed no danger \"in the sexual field\". In this case it becomes clear how brutally and humiliating Reich laws shaped the lives of Jewish people.\nIn 1938, there were again many major changes for Jews. From June onwards Jews were not allowed to own more than 5000 Reichsmarks, from July onwards Jews had to have their identification cards re-issued, on which a clear \"J\" was now recognizable.\nThe discrimination and isolation of the jewish population continued in 1938. Jewish children were kept away from \"Aryan\" peers more and more.\nAt the end of 1938, Jews were completely banned from owning shops. In addition, from 1939 on jewish citizens without typical jewish names had to add the names Israel or Sara to their first names.\nMost jewish residents felt well integrated into the German population, as many families had lived in Germany for several generations and even fought alongside the Germans in World War I. When the German government began to distribute targeted anti-Semitic propaganda such as newspaper articles and inflammatory films, the social position of Jews in society quickly changed. This is how the image of a stereotypical Jew was spread in society. For example, the children were asked to paint the \"Jew\" or to describe him in an essay.\nA \"Jewish face\" was also used at the main entrance of the Erlangen town hall as the underside of a door knocker. So if you knocked, his face was hit with a swastika.\nSo the discrimination in society against the jewish population grew.\nIf the propaganda was not effective enough or if they violated the norm, the residents of Erlangen were punished with other measures. For example, the director of the Marie-Theresien-Gymnasium was released into retirement when he had removed a teacher's anti-Semitic message. Many Jews were deprived of their doctoral degrees and suffered economic and legal disadvantages. In addition to these disadvantages, many also suffered psychological aftereffects.\nFinal solution:\nAfter the protection against dismissal for all jewish citizens was lifted in April 1939, they had to leave their homes and move into so-called Jewish houses. In Erlangen these houses were in the Raumerstraße 11, Kirchenstraße 8, Einhornstraße 5, Ostliche-Stadtmauer-Straße 7 and Bismarckstraße 20 and 26. Most of their property was \"Aryanized\", which means it was sold cheaply to citizens of the Reich. In September, Jews were banned from going out after 8 p.m., and in summer after 9 p.m.\nFrom April 24 in 1941, Jews were banned from using public transport, and from May 15, they were banned from keeping pets. In June they had to hand over all of their expendable items of clothing, all \"full Jews\" from the age of six had to wear a yellow star on their left breast.\nAt the end of November 1941, the first wave of deportations began. This affected ten Jews in Erlangen, all of whom lived in the Kirchenstrasse 8.\nThe second wave took place in March 1942. The third wave in September, it mainly affected the elderly and sick. They all were transported to the Theresienstadt concentration camp.\nThe last jewish woman in Erlangen, Hildegard Laink-Vissing, was deported to Auschwitz in 1943. Erlangen was officially \"free of Jews\" from February 2nd.";

String txt_Reichsprogromnacht_en = "The trigger that caused the Night of Broken Glass was the assassination attempt on the german embassy secretary Ernst vom Rath in Paris on the 7th of November 1938. The acts of violence of the national socialists intensified in the night from the 9th to the 10th of November. Arguing, that the response to the assassination attempt is resonable, the NSDAP and the SA initiated further violent actions against the jewish population. Jewish graveyards, synagogues and shops were destroyed throughout the whole German Reich. Furthermore about 30.000 jewish citizens were evicted, arrested and deported to concentration camps.\nThe atmosphere in Fürth and Nuremberg escalated quickly while the anniversary of the “Hitlerputsch”, the coup of the national socialists in 1923, was still celebrated in Erlangen. During the night it's plausable that the Gestapo-headoffice in Nuremberg gave the order to arrest all jews. The imprisonment of all jews living in Erlangen was an act led by the police and supported by the SA. At about 2.30 am the troops began to invade the homes of jewish citizens to imprison them. The innocent people were brought to the inner courtyard of the city hall, where they had to wait for many hours.\n\nA time witness, Lotte Ansbacher, who was 16 years old at the time described that they were left outside in the cold and wet for a long time. The children were screaming. Her mother got sick. She depicted the night as terrific.\n\nAlongside other imprisoned jews from Baiersdorf and Forth, who were abducted to Erlangen, they had to suffer further inhumane treatment. At the same time their homes, shops and their prayer room were plundered and destroyed by residents. Neither the police nor other residents intervened.\nThe recordings of the Benesi’s living room from the year 1937 and from the Night of Broken Glass show the brutal change happening in the life of the jewish family.\nAt noon the imprisoned jewish men had to walk a so called “Demütigungsmarsch” (a walk of humiliation) from the city hall to the official prison of Erlangen. There they were put into trucks to be transported to the prison in Nuremberg. The women and children were put into a shelter for homeless people located at the Wöhrmühle. The women and children were allowed to return to their homes after three days. The men were only released under the condition of reporting to the police station on a daily basis and procuring emigration documents. The jewish graveyard in Erlangen was not affected by the Night of Broken Glass. But on the 28th of May 1939 gravestones were knocked over. There were no reports in local newspapers.";

String txt_IsraelitischerFriedhof_en = "There are 171 Jewish cemeteries in the Free State of Bavaria of which 45 are concentration camp graveyards. Jewish cemeteries and the graves themselves are east-facing, meaning they directly face Jerusalems’ direction. The cemetery is called Beth Hachajim or Beth Olam which means \"house of life\" or \"house of eternity\". Those names symbolize the evanescence of life on the one hand and confirm the thought of eternal life after death on the other. That's why the gravestones are not decorated in a special way but left for nature to overgrow them with ivy and other plants. In remembrance of the dead, little stones are placed on top of the gravestone which is comparable to leaving flowers at a Christian grave.\nThe Jewish community in Erlangen buried their members in Baiersdorf until 1891. The inauguration of the new cemetery for the Jewish community was performed by the rabbi Dr. Jakob Neuburger, who was the rabbi for the Jewish community in Fürth. But until this could happen there was a lot of work to do because antisemitism already existed long before the NS-regime took over the power in Germany. It took a total of 13 years for the community to find the right place to bury their members because the city council objected to many of the suggested properties. Reasons for the objection were asthetical concerns or the property being too close to the street. After that there is a long period of time not documenting anything about the cemetery and even in the \"Reichspogrommnacht\" there were no noticeable damages. But only half a year later the first gravestones were overthrown and soon after all the graves were damaged. In 1943 the cemetery keeper prevented the flattening of the whole cemetery. After the end of the war some former Jewish citizens of Erlangen, who had been serving in the US army visited the cemetery. In 1945 the gravestones were established again in a process of reparations. The cemetery was declared a memorial in 1979. Four years after that a commemorative plaque was installed in remembrance of all Jewish people who lived in Erlangen from 1933 until 1945. The cemetery was consecrated again in 2002 due to a large reinforcement of Jewish people from 1995 until 2000. A Triple-memorial was installed to honor the euthanasia victims, the Jews who were killed in concentration camps and the Russian Jews who died in service of the Red Army.";

String txt_JuedischesLebenHeute_en = "Today’s Jewish community in Erlangen is probanly not only the youngest, but also the smallest of its kind in Germany.When it was founded in the year of 2000 it had almost 300 members, including 130 Jewish Orthodox immigrants from the former Soviet Union.These immigrated to Germany in 1995 and still make up a large proportion of the community’s members today.In addition, 20% of the members are international Jews who came to Erlangen in order for their jobs.Because of this variety the community attaches great importance to building a bond between the different cultures.This includes that the church service is held in Hebrew but translations into Russian and German are available.\nThe community practices their faith in the prayer room in the Hauptsreet, which was inaugurated in April in the year 2000 and financed among other ways by donations from the city of Erlangen.In the same year a Torah scroll was donated from New York.But the founding of the community in 2000 was not the first attempt to give Jewish life in Erlangen a permanent place.As early as in the 1980s a new center of beliefs for the Erlangen Jews was to be established.Unfortunately this was thwarted by the murder of the Rabbi Shlomo Levin and his partner Frida Poeschke.In addition to his work as a rabbi,Levin was known for his publishing house “Ner-Tamit” which means “eternal light”.He also worked with  great effort against the remaining anti-Semitism and for improving the relationship between Christians and Jews, for which he was awarded the Federal Cross of Merit,1st Class.Frida Poetschke was also firmly anchored in the public life of Erlangen as the widow of the former mayor Michael Poetschke.The anti-semetically motived murder of the couple shook Erlangen deeply and led to a delay of the re-establishment of a Jewish community by twenty years.\nAfter the aforementionmed re-establishment, operations of the Jewish cemetary, which had been orphaned since its closure in 1939,were resumed in 2002.As a result, Jewish life in erlangen has finally had a permanent place agin for almost twenty years.";

String txt_JuedischesLebenNSZeit_en = "At the present time, anti-Semitism and the hostility towards Jews is most of the time associated with the Nazi regime under Adolf Hitler. After further reflection it becomes obvious that the hatred towards Jews was not created by the Nazis, it’s much deeper anchored. This hostility goes back to antiquity. The following text gives you a short overview from the Empire to the Weimar Republic.\nThe history of the Jewish community begins shortly before the actual establishment of the Empire, when in 1861 the right of free settlement was made possible. After many applications to settle down, the cloth merchant Sigmund Weinstock received a permit to settle down and conduct his trade in the city - as long as his food supply was secured.\nThe first legal basis for equal rights of german Jews was the constitution of the German Empire in 1871, which turned Jewish residents into equal citizens. The advancing industrialization also increased the social mobility of the Jewish population, which led to many of them moving directly to Erlangen from the surrounding communities. Today some of these communities are parts of Erlangen - for example Bruck.\nIn 1873 an independent Jewish community was formed in Erlangen, five years later it already had 178 members. However, it was and still is one of the smallest Jewish communities.\nIn the fields of art, culture and science, parts of the Jewish population excelled through special achievements, for example the prominent Magnus Hirschfeld and Albert Einstein.\nThe late 19th century can be considered positively for the Jewish citizens of Erlangen. There were many business people and Jewish professors who were respected, successful and highly valued by the general public. As an example, you could name the physicians Prof. Rosenthal and Prof. Herz, both of whom had been granted honorary citizenship. Herz even was donated a memorial in Erlangen - the first memorial for a Jew in Germany. Today you can only find a memorial plaque on the Huguenot Square - because the statue got destroyed in 1914 by citizens of Erlangen - this is also evidence of the social anti-Semitism that had not been overcome but continued to affect the lives of the Jews.\nDuring the First World War they were accused of shirking, although around 96,000 Jewish soldiers fought ambitiously and patriotically in the German army. In Erlangen for example, Jakob Wassermann, Isaak Dingfelder, Berthold Stern and a few others who also received military awards - Berthold Stein even received the Iron Cross first class.\nThe same happened during the November Revolution of 1918: Jewish citizens were assumed to have sympathy for the radical left currents whereas the reality of life for many Jews was determined by involvement in parties of the middle class.\nThese are only two of numerous examples that illustrate how right-wing forces systematically tried to devalue the reputation of the Jewish minority.\nThe reforms of the law which started in 1871 were supplemented in the Weimar Constitution by the enactment of further laws to protect Jews. For example, the prohibition of discrimination against them in public service (Article 109 and 128) or the independence of civil rights from religious beliefs (Article 137). But this apparent progress was not reflected in the minds and behavior of some people, as regional examples from Erlangen also show. Especially in the course of the increasing radicalization in the final phase of the Weimar Republic and the rise of National Socialism, the Jewish population was put under increasing pressure.\nIn 1929, the National Socialists mainly used the needs of the population caused by the global economic crisis to propagate their anti-Semitic ideology.\nThe National Socialist weekly paper \"Kampf\" first attacked a Jewish businessman publicly in August 1931. Berthold Stern, the owner of a clothing store, was accused because one of the clothes rails was placed on the sidewalk as it had always been done. Like him, many other Jewish people had to experience how daily situations led to difficulties and how the anti-Semitism of the population started to show.\nThe Jewish religion teacher Justin Fränkel also had to endure several insults and abuses on the street in 1932 because of his faith. In addition, he was also publicly discredited in an article in the weekly paper “Kampf”.\nGenerally, the paradigm shift triggered by the progress in legislation should be recognized, which helped Judaism in Germany to achieve equality. With the election of the NSDAP and Hitler as Reich Chancellor, however, the part of the population that had previously practiced anti-Semitism finally prevailed and made it an official political direction from 1933 onwards.";

String txt_Stolpersteine_en = "Stolpersteine are a project designed by the German artist Gunther Demnig. The first one was laid in 1992. By now it is the biggest decentralized cenotaph of the world with about 7500 Stolpersteine (2019) in over 21 countries. The block is placed in front of the last voluntary chosen residence of the people who have been persecuted by the NS-regime. The project aims to give these people their names back. Demnig is also criticizing that centralized memorials do not draw enough attention to the fate of those people. Furthermore centralized memorials are always placed in locations where said people experienced something terrible whereas their last residence might be associated with more joyful memories.\nThere are also critical voices. Most critics point out that the Stolpersteine are harmful because they are placed in the ground and people could potentially step on them. The most prominent example is Munich, where the laying was stopped and already laid Stolpersteine had to be removed. Another problem is that the blocks can easily be vandalized because of their decentralized structure.\nIn Erlangen the initiative was brought up as a topic to the city council by Ilse Sponsel, who is the ambassador of the former Jewish citizens of Erlangen. The Stolpersteine were laid in 2007. There are likewise Stolpersteine for the victims of the former psychiatric facility at the Maximiliansplatz but their historical correctness is not always proven. At the moment there is a huge scientific concideration of this part of the history of Erlangen. Closely knit to this topic is the debate about whether and how the buildings will be used in the future. The first approach to completely tear down the building was dismissed and in its place plans to use the building for remembrance were implemented.";